post_text:
ASTEC recently returned to an in-person blended learning model. Scholars in Mr. Dillyn Sprecher's sixth-grade ELA class were asked to complete a getting-to-know-me activity and describe their favorite thing as a sixth-grade scholar.

Despite everything, a sixth-grader can entertain themselves with (Tik Tok, Fornite, etc.), one scholar answered, "What I like about being a sixth grader is me meeting my seven nice teachers."

This scholar's response is a great reminder of why in-person classes are so important in building scholar-teacher relationships. Mr. Sprecher’s response was, “On behalf of the entire sixth-grade team of teachers, what we like about being sixth-grade teachers is meeting all of our new wonderful sixth-grade scholars!"

post_text:
As with other high schools, students must have a parking permit. Other schools charge up to $50 for parking permits. ASTEC charges only $10 for the year and proceeds go to the Studrent Council for school events.

Students and employees must have parking permits for a number of reasons. When cars speed In the parking lot, the Mall and the school need to identify the vehicle. Required drug dogs are randomly brought to the campus building and parking lots. Occasionally there are accidents in the parking lot and the Mall and police must be able to identify the owner of the vehicle. These are but a few of the times cars need to be identified.

Student drivers have been reminded daily since school started and were given ample time to register their vehicles. As a last resort, unregistered vehicles will be towed.

post_text:
What should my children be doing on days they learn from home?

Because our scholars attend school only twice a week (two hours per class), distance learning is supposed to supplement the learning of the scholars for when they are not at school and so we can still keep the scholars Engaged and learning.

Your child's teachers have provided assignments/activities for the days he/she is not in school that will allow him to be engaged in the content and help reinforce the material covered throughout his classes.

Currently, most teachers are assigning paper and pencil assignments (something that does not have to be turned in online) because we are aware that not every scholar has access to the internet. Once we have endured every scholar has internet access, we will shift to Google Classroom (your child's teachers will cover that in more detail) where his assignments will be posted from then on.

post_text:
Congratulations to ASTEC senior, Kimberly Alvarez, who was inducted into the 2020-21 Oklahoma City Youth Council in early August.

Ms. Alvarez is one of only 18 Oklahoma City high school students chosen to be on the Youth Council. As part of that role, she will work with her ward's City Council member and City staff to learn about the challenges and successes of municipal government. She will also help address issues affecting Oklahoma City's youth in a series of on-line meetings, seminars and more.

Kimberly is another example of excellence at ASTEC Charter Schools!
https://www.okc.gov/Home/Components/News/News/3519/5296

Congratulations to one of our ASTEC stars, high school history teacher Christy Hanna, one of only 98 teachers nationwide selected for a National History Day Summer Webinar Series.

This new course focuses on using online Library of Congress resources to develop and support historical arguments and is a feature of NHD’s membership in the Library of Congress Teaching with Primary Sources (TPS) Consortium. Over the course of the series, Ms. Hanna has explored digitized primary sources from the Library of Congress, engaged in four live webinar programs and discussions with fellow educators from across the country, and developed resources to use with students in her classroom.

post_text:
Elementary School Orientation Announcement:

As you know, guidelines and protocols are changing rapidly as more is learned of the COVID-19 virus.

ASTEC is working hard to stay up with these changes and to make adjustments as needed.

We appreciate your patience and understanding.

One of the purposes of Orientation Night is for parents to submit final enrollment paperwork and to meet the teachers and administrators.

Recently, a number of families have completed that paperwork. That means we have fewer than expected families who will need to come to orientation. Therefore, we are consolidating all elementary orientations to August 4th at 6:00 pm. Again, this will be held at 2401 NW 23rd in the ASTEC Auditorium.

The orientation will be filmed and posted on our Facebook page on August 5th.

Again those parents who have turned in all of their forms are not to come to the school for orientation but should watch the orientation on Facebook.

We hope this is more convenient for our families.

3 IPV (polio)

2 Hep A (hepatitis A)

3 Hep B (hepatitis B)

Seasonal influenza (flu)

Watch history unfold as NASA and SpaceX launch astronauts Robert Behnken and Douglas Hurley to the ISS on Wednesday, May 27. This mission marks the first time since the retirement of the space shuttle in 2011 that humans will fly to the space station from U.S. soil.

Set a reminder to tune for joint NASA/SpaceX coverage starting at 12:15 p.m. EDT, with liftoff currently targeted for 4:33 p.m. EDT. 🚀

post_text:
ASTEC is proud to announce that our current middle school Co-Teacher, Cindy Millican, has been promoted to Director of Special Education. She will oversee the ASTEC special education programs for pre-K through 12th grade.
UMB
Ms. Millican earned a Bachelor’s and Master’s Degrees in Special Education from the University of Oklahoma. Later, she earned a Master's Degree in Educational Administration and Curriculum Studies from the University of Oklahoma.

Ms. Millican taught for eight years in Moore, Oklahoma before coming to ASTEC. She is excited to be a part of the ASTEC Comet Community.

Cindy lives in Moore with her husband, Eric and their daughter, Mollie.

post_text:
Mandatory online classes begin Monday, April 6 at 8:30 a.m.

You must have WI-FI. Free internet service information has been given to families.

Students must sign in and complete the daily assignments in each class before 11:59 PM in order to be counted present.

The "10-day/10% absences" rule is state law. Parents of students who do not sign in will be contacted, If a scholar continues not to sign in or do adequate work, ASTEC will follow the state law regarding consequences.

Students will receive assignments and instruction through Google Classroom.

If you have any issues logging into Google Classroom, email your first period teacher.

Teachers will be available for a virtual face-to-face meeting each day from 12:30-2:00.

You will receive instructions on the first day about how to access the live video meetings.

If you have a laptop, Chromebook, or tablet with a camera, you will be able to see your teacher, and your teacher will be able to see you.

Please check Facebook and the ASTEC website daily for important updates.

ASTEC Charter Schools added 7 new photos.
February 19 at 10:48 AM ·

Economics is an essential aspect of our social and political geography. Our scholars accessed the International Monetary Fund online to learn about trade relationships throughout the world playing a real-world trading game! Economics also plays a vital role in nations expressing their governmental systems.

Students used the game “Rock, Paper, Scissors” where one scholar would start with 1 bag of Fruit Snacks and another with 10 they would play the game until someone got all the snacks in an effort to understand capitalism/democracy then the game would model communism/command economy as well as socialism.

ASTEC scholars did a fantastic job of creating real-world scenarios of possible social issues that might arise in each type of economic system.

post_text:
ASTEC Charter Schools takes student safety very seriously. ASTEC has a number of safety protocols in place to ensure our scholars are safe. As soon as there is any perceived threat to the school or one of its scholars either in person or posted on the Internet, the Oklahoma City Police Special Unit is called to investigate and provide ASTEC administration with the credibility of the threat.

Students making threats of any kind or disparaging ASTEC students or employees is illegal. Students violating this law will be long-term suspended and removed from the school.

Parents, please talk to your students about the seriousness of their posts. Please monitor their posts.

Respectfully,

Dr. Freda Deskin
CEO and Founder

Mr. Shannon Grimes
Superintendent

The 2020 ASTEC Middle School Spelling Bee Champion has been c-r-o-w-n-e-d! Scholars at ASTEC recently competed in the Middle School Spelling Bee, facilitated by Mr. Dillon Sprecher, sixth grade English teacher.

From classroom qualifiers to an eighteen-student final, only one speller remained victorious! Eighth-grader Marvin Leal Hernadez claimed the top prize with the runner-up spot going to sixth-grader Erick Garay. Both scholars will move on to regional competition to represent ASTEC. Join us at Douglas High School Auditorium at 6:30 p.m. on February 11, 2020, to cheer on our two amazing ASTEC spellers!

Eighth-grader Marvin Leal Hernadez claimed the top prize with the runner-up spot going to sixth-grader Erick Garay. Both scholars will move on to regional competition to represent ASTEC. Join us at Douglas High School Auditorium at 6:30 p.m. on February 11, 2020, to cheer on our two amazing ASTEC spellers!

The lottery will be held on April 1, 2020 during the day. You do not have to be present for the lottery. You will be notified of acceptance after the lottery.

post_text:
We've got spirit, how about you????

ASTEC's Spirit Week is Monday, December 9th through Friday, December 13th.

Monday - Pajama day: Pajamas have to be acceptable, and administration will be the decision-maker, so be conservative. Shoes are required.

Tuesday - Meme Day: Come dressed as your favorite Meme.

Wednesday - Decade Day: Dress in the fashion of your favorite decade. 50’s, 60’s, 70’s, 80’s, 90’s.

Thursday -Twin Day: Choose a partner or partners. Dress alike and accessorize to look like you are twins.

Friday is Spirit Day: Wear your favorite ASTEC shirt and your favorite shoes. Wear your uniform bottoms. (No open-toed shoes or high heels).

It is a great day to be a Comet!

Darwin was born and raised in Oklahoma City and considers his greatest contribution and accomplishment in education to be consistently motivating, encouraging and setting an unwavering high level of expectation for all students!

post_text:
From Mr. Danny Porter, ASTEC Rowing Coach

Fall Regatta-

What an amazing weekend. It was a beautiful night this Saturday as we competed in our Fall Youth Rowing League Rowing Regatta on the Oklahoma River. Both our High School and Middle School teams showed great resilience, determination, and athleticism.

Our Middle school team qualified for the grand finale race and won! However, after a minor time adjustment, we placed 2nd overall. I was overwhelmed with pride in their performance. Our High school team did a phenomenal job.

Our varsity boat won first in their race which qualified them for the grand final. In our final race, ASTEC Comets took 3rd place! Although we did not bring home the…

ASTEC Charter Schools Have Partnered with Choose Love Communities to Present ‘30 Days of Gratitude’ in November
We are pleased to partner with The Jesse Lewis Choose Love Movement™ and celebrate ‘30 Days of Gratitude’ throughout November to teach and inspire people to live a life with gratitude.

‘30 Days of Gratitude’ will share ways to become more grateful on social media. Daily posts on Facebook and Twitter will delve into thought-provoking and inspiring ways to be grateful as well as revealing the scientific benefits of gratitude. Resources will be provided to help begin a more fulfilling life through gratitude and Choosing Love every day.
